`IFormFile` buffers the entire body into memory — that's the root cause. Instead, read the raw `Request.Body` stream (or use `MultipartReader` for multipart forms) and write chunks directly to disk.

**Key changes:**

```csharp
// Program.cs

// 1. Raise the max request body size (default is ~28MB)
builder.WebHost.ConfigureKestrel(k =>
    k.Limits.MaxRequestBodySize = 2L * 1024 * 1024 * 1024); // 2 GB

// 2. Stream-to-disk endpoint
app.MapPost("/upload", async (HttpRequest request) =>
{
    // Disable request buffering so ASP.NET doesn't hold it in memory
    request.EnableBuffering(bufferThreshold: 0);

    var boundary = request.GetMultipartBoundary();
    if (string.IsNullOrEmpty(boundary))
        return Results.BadRequest("Expected a multipart request.");

    var reader = new MultipartReader(boundary, request.Body);
    var section = await reader.ReadNextSectionAsync();

    while (section is not null)
    {
        if (ContentDispositionHeaderValue.TryParse(
                section.ContentDisposition, out var cd)
            && cd.IsFileDisposition())
        {
            var fileName = Path.GetRandomFileName();       // safe name
            var path = Path.Combine("/tmp/uploads", fileName);

            // Stream directly to disk in 64 KB chunks — no large buffer
            await using var fs = File.Create(path);
            await section.Body.CopyToAsync(fs);

            return Results.Ok(new { path });
        }
        section = await reader.ReadNextSectionAsync();
    }

    return Results.BadRequest("No file found.");
})
.DisableAntiforgery();
```

**Why this works:**

| | `IFormFile` | `MultipartReader` |
|---|---|---|
| Memory | Buffers entire file | Streams in small chunks |
| 2 GB file | OOM crash | ~64 KB peak usage |

**Don't forget:**

- Add `using Microsoft.AspNetCore.WebUtilities;` and `using Microsoft.Net.Http.Primitives;` for `MultipartReader` / `GetMultipartBoundary()`.
- If behind a reverse proxy (nginx, IIS), raise its body-size limit too (`client_max_body_size 2g;` for nginx).
- For **non-multipart** raw binary uploads, skip the reader entirely and just `await request.Body.CopyToAsync(fileStream)`.
